        "Answer": "I will advise the trustee that she has nothing to pay in annual income taxes because the trust’s taxable income is zero. This is so because the amount of income to be distributed annually to the beneficiary is a deduction from the gross income of the trust but must be reported as income of the beneficiary (Section 61(A), NIRC). No, the trustee has to pay the income tax on the trust’s net income determined annually if the income is required to be accumulated. Once a taxable trust is established, its net income is either taxable to the trust, represented by the trustee, or o the beneficiary depending on the provision for distribution of income following the one-layer taxation scheme (Section 61(A), NIRC). (BAR 2009)"
